That said I still would love to pursue illustration and art more seriously full time, it just looks like I’m not making it before I’m 40, and that’s going to have to be fine!

This is just my personal story of getting by with a “creative career” for the past 12 years, I didn’t have a parent that gave me $ (she did give me food and still does love u mom) and I didn’t live at home, I didn’t always have healthcare, and I’ve lived in NYC the whole time.

So! TL;DR being broke sucks, you probably have a bunch of marketable skills that can help you use your talent and eye to make money, and then the rest is up to your individual vision to figure out your way to making art professionally.

Illustration also tends to be a single component of a larger product. So you’re creating something that has a smaller part of an overall budget. This is the issue I think with writing as well sometimes.
Now I know how to make money as a freelance designer, and as an illustrator, but I think it would be impossible to support myself solely on the product of illustration. It’s an undervalued product.

When you end up tabling you’re artistic goals for professional ones, you do end up in a place where it’s easier to find and make more money at jobs because you have a higher baseline. You do get burned out on work and do have less time to pursue creative goals, though.

My next job was essentially the same but producing display ads at a media company - this was at least closer to the editorial illustration goals I had and paid a LOT more.
I ended up there for 6 years leaving as an art director at a much higher salary (~80k), and I learned a lot.

I learned like, valuable design and production skills but did no illustration work. I would practice and pursue on my own, but I was tired and still broke with 2 roommates, and I worked a second job as a waitress on weekends for extra money.

I took the first job that offered me a full time salary (32k/year with benefits) there was no ACA so I needed the insurance. I had basic html/css experience and was extremely adept at photoshop, so I became a web designer/producer. I was there for 3 years, left making 38k/year.

I’ve seen a lot of good threads in response to this with functional advice on how to live your life on a stressed income. That’s important to know!
